04817nam a22007335i 9780812293500DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984546799  a97808122935007 a10.9783/97808122935002doi  a(DE-B1597)480843  a(OCoLC)965772832  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA04a302/.122304aThe Economy of Hope /ced. by Hirokazu Miyazaki, Richard Swedberg. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b5 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tThe Economy of Hope: An Introduction -- tChapter 1. A Sociological Approach to Hope in the Economy -- tChapter 2. Mercantilist-Utopian Projects in Eighteenth- Century Sweden -- tChapter 3. Hope Turned Upside Down: How the Prospects for a Communist Utopia Were Dashed in 1950s Romania -- tChapter 4. Hope and Society in Japan -- tChapter 5. Is the Law Hopeful? -- tChapter 6. When and How Does Hope Spring Eternal in Personal and Popular Economics? Thoughts from West Africa to America -- tChapter 7. Obama’s Hope: An Economy of Belief and Substance -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHope is an integral part of social life. Yet, hope has not been studied systematically in the social sciences. Editors Hirokazu Miyazaki and Richard Swedberg have collected essays that investigate hope in a broad range of socioeconomic situations and phenomena across time and space and from a variety of disciplinary vantage points. Contributors survey the resilience of hope, and the methodological implications of studying hope, in such experiences as farm collectivization in mid-twentieth-century communist Romania, changing employment relations under Japan's neoliberal reform during the first decade of the twenty-first century, the dynamics of innovation and replication in a West African niche economy, and Barack Obama's 2008 political campaign of hope in the midst of the unfolding global financial crisis.The Economy of Hope shifts the analytic of anthropological and sociological investigations from knowledge to hope, presents case studies on the loss of collective hope, and concludes by offering techniques for replicating hope. In the hands of Miyazaki and Swedberg and their distinguished contributors, hope becomes not only a method of knowledge but also an essential framework for the sociocultural analysis of economic phenomena.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHope.1 aGenda, Yuji, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuyer, Jane I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiyazaki, Hirokazu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiyazaki, Hirokazu, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRiles, Annelise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwedberg, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwedberg, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVerdery, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066591840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229350040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293500423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812293500.jpg  a978-3-11-066591-8  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA